eden","1510–Male":"1510–Overleden","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1535":"1535","1510":"1510","1549":"1549","Denham, Mid Suffolk district, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Denham, Suffolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"England","Saint John the Baptist church, Denham, Mid Suffolk district, Suffolk, England":"Denham, Suffolk, England"},"en":{"1510–":"1510–Deceased","1535–Female":"1535–Deceased","1510–Male":"1510–Deceased","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1535":"1535","1510":"1510","1549":"1549","Denham, Mid Suffolk district, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Denham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Saint John the Baptist church, Denham, Mid Suffolk district, Suffolk, England":"Denham, Suffolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Arney","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: perhaps from the Middle English personal name <i>Ernwi</i> (Old English <i>Earnwīg</i>, composed of the elements <i>earn</i> ‘eagle’ + <i>wīg</i> ‘battle’). If so, the surname shows the unexceptional loss of <i>-w-</i> in the unstressed syllable following <i>-n-</i>.","In some cases an Americanized form of German or Swedish   Arne  .","In some cases also an Americanized form of Norwegian <b>Arnøy</b>: habitational name from any of a number of farmsteads named for the islands on which they stand; the original derivation of such names being either from the Old Norse personal name <i>Arni</i>, or from <i>ǫrn</i> ‘eagle’ + <i>øy</i> ‘island’."],"variants":[{"name":"Arne","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Juel.","English (northern), Swedish, and German: from the (medieval) personal name <i>Arne</i>, a short form of   Arnold   or, in Scandinavia, any of the many other Norse names of which <i>arn</i> ‘eagle’ is the first element, for example <i>Arnbjörn</i>, <i>Arnfinn</i>, and <i>Arnsten</i>.","English: habitational name from Arne, a place in Dorset, which is most probably named with Old English <i>ærn</i> ‘building, house’."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":39,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705202,"age":48,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705205,"age":59,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Robert Arney was born in 1510, in Denham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 daughter. He died in England."},"et":{"1510–":"1510–Surnud","1535–Female":"1535–Surnud","1510–Male":"1510–Surnud","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1535":"1535","1510":"1510","1549":"1549","Denham, Mid Suffolk district, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Denham, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Saint John the Baptist church, Denham, Mid Suffolk district, Suffolk, England":"Denham, Suffolk, England"},"fi":{"1510–":"1510–Kuollut","1535–Female":"1535–Kuollut","1510–Male":"1510–Kuollut","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1535":"1535","1510":"1510","1549":"1549","Denham, Mid Suffolk district, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Denham, Suffolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"England","Saint John the Baptist church, Denham, Mid Suffolk district, Suffolk, England":"Denham, Suffolk, England"},"fr":{"1510–":"1510–Décédé","1535–Female":"1535–Décédée","1510–Male":"1510–Décédé","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1535":"1535","1510":"1510","1549":"1549","Denham, Mid Suffolk district, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Denham, Suffolk, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","England":"Angleterre","Saint John the Baptist church, Denham, Mid Suffolk district, Suffolk, England":"Denham, Suffolk, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Robert Arney est né en 1510, à Denham, Suffolk, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Il a eu au moins 1 fille. Il est décédé à Angleterre."},"de":{"1510–":"1510–Verstorben","1535–Female":"1535–Verstorben","1510–Male":"1510–Verstorben","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1535":"1535","1510":"1510","1549":"1549","Denham, Mid Suffolk district, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Denham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Engl